{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"PASS 1 plan-review (criterion T1 — prior-art / novel-architecture justification) for the cross-referenced docs plan \"Docs: private-repo credentials, descriptive errors, ref/source semantics, HMAC trust model\" (xref'd here via the EFS/NFS flock caveat in AC5). Recorded here as the addressable anchor ticket.\n\nAFFIRMATIONS (T1 — these already pass):\n- Prior-art-aware attestation framing: the plan documents \"the in-toto Statement shape\" rather than inventing a bespoke attestation envelope — it aligns the HMAC attestation to an established standard (in-toto). This is exactly the anti-reinvention posture T1(a)/(b) asks for.\n- Trust-model limits stated against the established property set: the plan explicitly documents that HMAC gives \"integrity + intra-domain authenticity only; no non-repudiation / public verifiability / transparency\" — i.e. it consciously scopes its divergence from the fuller signature/transparency model (in-toto/sigstore-style), which is the Rule-of-Three / anti-repackaging justification T1(b) wants.\n- No reinvention of crypto machinery: the HMAC signing surface already exists and is documented (src/rebar/signing.py; docs/reuse-surface.md §1) — this ticket documents/reuses it, it does not introduce a parallel signing path. (Verified: HMAC-SHA256 over a canonical (ticket_id, manifest) payload, environment-keyed, head_sha freshness binding.)\n\nFINDINGS (T1):\n- [ ] Pin the exact in-toto Statement spec the doc claims conformance to. The plan promises to document \"the in-toto Statement shape\" but does not name WHICH in-toto Statement/predicate version (e.g. Statement v0.1 vs v1, and the `predicateType` used) the HMAC attestation maps onto — for an authoritative trust-model doc this is a load-bearing, unresolved standard-conformance assertion (T1(c)). Recommend the doc state the precise in-toto spec version + predicate type it conforms to (or explicitly state it borrows only the Statement *shape* and is NOT a conformant in-toto attestation, given it uses HMAC rather than the in-toto signing/DSSE envelope).\n  - criteria: [T1]\n  - location: plan \"What\" bullet 4 / AC4 (\"the in-toto Statement shape are documented\")\n  - evidence: plan phrase \"the in-toto Statement shape\"; ABSENCE of a named in-toto Statement/predicate version; codebase fact — attestation is HMAC-SHA256 (signing.py:51), not a DSSE/signature envelope, so an explicit \"shape-only, not conformant\" caveat prevents an over-claim.\n  - suggested_fix: In the HMAC trust-model doc, add a line of the form: \"The attestation borrows the in-toto Statement <vX> shape (predicateType `<...>`) but is signed with environment-keyed HMAC-SHA256, not a DSSE/in-toto signature envelope — so it is shape-compatible, not a conformant in-toto attestation (consistent with the documented limits: no non-repudiation / public verifiability).\"\n\nNo other T1 findings — the credential / fail-closed / ref-source-semantics content does not cross a novel-architecture or unverified-capability bright-line (credential helpers/deploy keys/tokens are well-trodden git-fetch prior art needing no prior-art search)."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782522372368391001,"uuid":"b35d961e-3323-4ce2-a9e8-dc19b512c2cb"}